We recognize and celebrate Juneteenth, a day that commemorates freedom, resilience, and the enduring pursuit of equality. It marks the day when news of emancipation reached enslaved African Americans in Texas, more than two years after the Emancipation Proclamation was issued. As we celebrate this important part of American history, we encourage our children to learn about the values of freedom, unity, respect, and hope. We honor the contributions, culture, and achievements of African Americans and reflect on the importance of building a brighter future for all. ❤️🖤💚✨ <hr><br>

📅 <strong>Date: Friday, June 19, 2026</strong><br>


